        "user": "How does \"off-token route\" differ from prelinguistic cognition?",
        "assistant": "“Prelinguistic cognition” names the **human cognitive mode itself**: thinking, sensing, imagining, recognizing, or intending before words are attached.\n\n“Off-token route” names that same kind of capacity **as a route of access**—a way concepts can arise or be contacted without first passing through language-like symbols/tokens.\n\nSo the difference is mostly emphasis:\n\n- **Prelinguistic cognition**: the human mental content before language.  \n  - Example: a baby recognizing its mother’s face; a person feeling “something is wrong” before articulating why; seeing an image in the mind before describing it.\n\n- **Off-token route**: the pathway by which such content is reachable without tokens.  \n  - It contrasts humans with LLMs: humans can have felt-sense, perception, imagery, bodily intuition, etc., prior to naming, while an LLM can only access/process concepts through tokenized representations.\n\nIn short: **prelinguistic cognition is the kind of cognition; off-token route is the access-pathway framing of that cognition, especially in contrast to LLM token-dependence.**",
