        "user": "How does \"off-token route\" differ from embodied cognition?",
        "assistant": "“Embodied cognition” is the broader theory that human thinking is shaped by the body: perception, action, sensorimotor systems, emotion, posture, environment, and bodily interaction with the world.\n\n“Off-token route” is narrower and more specific: it names the human capacity to access cognition **before or outside tokens/language** — felt-sense, imagery, intuition, recognition, or meaning prior to naming — and contrasts that with LLMs, whose reachable concepts must pass through tokens.\n\nSo the difference:\n\n- **Embodied cognition**: cognition is grounded in bodily life and interaction with the world.  \n  - Example: understanding “grasp” partly through motor experience; solving a problem by manipulating objects; emotion influencing reasoning.\n\n- **Off-token route**: cognition can arise through a nonlinguistic route before being verbalized or tokenized.  \n  - Example: sensing the answer before knowing how to say it; visualizing a scene before describing it; recognizing a face without naming it.\n\nThey overlap because much off-token human cognition may be embodied: felt-sense, bodily intuition, perceptual recognition, spatial imagination, etc. But they are not identical.\n\nIn short: **embodied cognition explains where much human cognition is grounded; off-token route explains that humans can reach cognition through non-token pathways, whereas LLMs cannot.**",
