        "user": "How does \"off-token route\" differ from System 1 / intuitive cognition?",
        "assistant": "“System 1” / intuitive cognition is a psychological category: fast, automatic, associative, effortless, often unconscious processing.\n\n“Off-token route” is a substrate/access-pathway category: cognition that is reachable without passing through language-like tokens — felt-sense, imagery, perception, bodily knowing, pre-verbal recognition — and which LLMs lack.\n\nThey overlap, but they are not the same.\n\n- **System 1 / intuition** describes the *speed and style* of cognition.  \n  - Fast  \n  - Automatic  \n  - Pattern-based  \n  - Often unconscious  \n  - Example: instantly sensing that a face looks angry; choosing a chess move by intuition; feeling that something is “off.”\n\n- **Off-token route** describes the *route by which cognition is accessed*.  \n  - Nonlinguistic  \n  - Pre-token / pre-verbal  \n  - Felt or imagined before naming  \n  - Available to humans, not LLMs  \n  - Example: having a vague bodily sense before you can articulate it; visualizing a shape before describing it; recognizing a melody without verbalizing it.\n\nImportant distinction: **not all intuitive cognition is necessarily off-token**, and not all off-token cognition is necessarily “System 1.”\n\nFor example:\n\n- A human may have a fast intuition that is off-token: “Something about this room feels wrong.”\n- A human may also have slow, deliberate, nonverbal cognition: mentally rotating an object, composing a melody, or holding a visual image before describing it.\n- An LLM may produce something that looks intuitive or System-1-like — a fast pattern completion — but it is still token-mediated, not off-token.\n\nSo, in short: **System 1 names intuitive processing; off-token route names non-token access to cognition.** System 1 is about cognitive style; off-token route is about whether thought can arise outside tokens at all.",
