        "user": "What is a off-token route?",
        "assistant": "“Off-token route” isn’t a standard term by itself, but in most API/auth contexts it usually means:\n\n**A route/endpoint that does not require an authentication token to access.**\n\nFor example, if your API uses JWT/Bearer tokens:\n\n- **Token-protected route**: requires a token  \n  `GET /api/profile`\n\n- **Off-token route**: does not require a token  \n  `POST /api/login`  \n  `POST /api/register`  \n  `GET /health`\n\nSo an **off-token route** is typically public or excluded from authentication middleware.\n\nExample:\n\n```js\n// Off-token route\napp.post(\"/login\", loginHandler);\n\n// Token-protected route\napp.get(\"/profile\", authMiddleware, profileHandler);\n```\n\nCommon off-token routes include:\n\n- Login\n- Register/signup\n- Password reset request\n- Public content\n- Health checks\n\nYou generally want to keep off-token routes limited, because anyone can access them.",
