        "user": "How does \"off-token route\" differ from prelinguistic cognition?",
        "assistant": "They’re very different concepts from different domains.\n\n| Term | Domain | Meaning |\n|---|---|---|\n| **Off-token route** | Software/API/authentication | A route or endpoint that does **not require an auth token** to access. |\n| **Prelinguistic cognition** | Psychology/cognitive science | Thinking or mental processing that happens **before or without language**. |\n\nAn **off-token route** is a technical access-control idea. For example:\n\n```js\napp.post(\"/login\", loginHandler); // no token required\n```\n\nA **prelinguistic cognition** example would be an infant recognizing faces, tracking objects, feeling hunger, or learning cause and effect before they can speak.\n\nSo the difference is:\n\n- **Off-token route** = a public/unprotected software route.\n- **Prelinguistic cognition** = nonverbal or before-language mental processing.\n\nThey are not really comparable unless someone is using “off-token” metaphorically in an AI/LLM context to mean “processing not based on language tokens.” In that case, it would be somewhat closer to prelinguistic cognition, but still not the same: one is an engineered computational pathway, the other is a biological/cognitive capacity.",
